The modern notion of Knowledge Graphs (KGs) arose in the context of improving search engines [DBLP:journals/cacm/GutierrezS21]. 
 In 2012, the Google Knowledge Graph was proposed to boost search by ``things, not strings'' [GoogleKG]:
 when matching a string like ``Manuel Blum'' against web contents, the SE can recognize that the string likely references a real-world entity.
 This requires a structured repository of real-world entities, 
 their types (e.g., computer scientist), their attributes (e.g., birth date), and the relations between entities (e.g., Blum has birthplace Caracas).
 Figure (ref) shows a toy KG where nodes represent entities (rounded corners) or types
 (square corners), and edges represent the relations between them. KGs enable or enhance a variety of 
